In [ ]:
#By coloring the points based on their corresponding labels, we can visualize how the different classes are distributed in this space, and whether there are any clear patterns or clusters that separate them from each other.
idx = np.random.randint(x_train.shape[0], size=500)
x_train_sample = x_train[idx, :]
y_train_sample = y_train[idx]

# Fit PCA model to the data
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
x_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(x_train_sample.reshape(x_train_sample.shape[0], -1))

# Plot the scatterplot
plt.scatter(x_train_pca[:, 0], x_train_pca[:, 1], c=y_train[idx], cmap='tab10')
plt.colorbar()
plt.show()

# sample only 20k images for training
idx = np.random.randint(x_train.shape[0], size=20000) 
x_train = x_train[idx, :]
y_train = y_train[idx]
print('Shape of x_train: ',x_train.shape)
print('Shape of y_train: ',y_train.shape)

# specify input dimensions of each image
img_rows, img_cols = 28, 28
input_shape = (img_rows, img_cols, 1)

batch_size = 128
num_classes = 10

epochs = 20
# reshape x_train and x_test
x_train = x_train.reshape(x_train.shape[0], img_rows, img_cols, 1)
x_test = x_test.reshape(x_test.shape[0], img_rows, img_cols, 1)
print('Reshape of x_train: ',x_train.shape)
print('Reshape of x_test: ',x_test.shape)

# convert class labels from digits to one-hot encoded vectors
y_train = keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, num_classes)
y_test = keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, num_classes)
print('Shape of y_train: ',y_train.shape)

# convert int to float
x_train = x_train.astype('float32')
x_test = x_test.astype('float32')

# normalise
x_train /= 255
x_test /= 255

Shape of x_train:  (20000, 28, 28)
Shape of y_train:  (20000,)
Reshape of x_train:  (20000, 28, 28, 1)
Reshape of x_test:  (10000, 28, 28, 1)
Shape of y_train:  (20000, 10)

Model 1: Baseline Model

This is a basic CNN model for image classification that consists of three layers: a convolutional layer, a fully connected layer, and a softmax output layer. The convolutional layer contains 32 filters of size 3x3 and applies the relu activation function to each output. The fully connected layer contains 128 neurons and applies the relu activation function as well as a dropout regularization with rate of 0.5. The final softmax layer is used to output the class probabilities for the input image. The model is compiled with categorical cross-entropy loss and optimized using the Adam optimizer.

In [ ]:
model = Sequential()

# first conv layer
model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3),
                 activation='relu',
                 input_shape=input_shape))



# flatten and put a fully connected layer
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))

# softmax layer
model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

model.summary()

# usual cross entropy loss
model.compile(loss=keras.losses.categorical_crossentropy,
              optimizer='adam',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# fit the model
fit_model = model.fit(x_train, y_train,
          batch_size=batch_size,
          epochs=epochs,
          verbose=1,
          validation_data=(x_test, y_test))

# Save the model
model.save('BaseModel.h5')

# evaluate the model on test data
model.evaluate(x_test, y_test)

Model 2

The model has two convolutional layers with 32 and 64 filters respectively, each with a kernel size of 3x3 and a sigmoid activation function. The second convolutional layer is followed by a max pooling layer with a pool size of 2x2 and a dropout layer with a rate of 0.25.

After the convolutional layers, the output is flattened and passed to a fully connected layer with 128 neurons and a sigmoid activation function. This layer is followed by another dropout layer with a rate of 0.5, and finally a softmax layer with 10 neurons and a softmax activation function.

In [ ]:
# Add second conv layer & activation using sigmoid
model2 = Sequential()

input_shape = (28,28,1)
# First conv layer
model2.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3),
                 activation='sigmoid',
                 input_shape=input_shape))

# Second conv layer
model2.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3, 3), 
                 activation='sigmoid'))
model2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model2.add(Dropout(0.25))

# Flatten and put a fully connected layer
model2.add(Flatten())
model2.add(Dense(128, activation='sigmoid')) # Fully connected
model2.add(Dropout(0.5))

# Softmax layer
model2.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

model2.summary()

# Usual cross entropy loss
model2.compile(loss=keras.losses.categorical_crossentropy,
              optimizer='adam',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Fit the model
fit_model2 = model2.fit(x_train, y_train,
          batch_size=batch_size,
          epochs=epochs,
          verbose=1,
          validation_data=(x_test, y_test))

# Save the model
model2.save('Model2.h5')

# Evaluate the model on test data
model2.evaluate(x_test, y_test)

Model 3

The first convolutional layer uses a filter size of 4x4, a stride of (2,1), and applies the tanh activation function. The second convolutional layer uses a filter size of 4x4 and the tanh activation function, followed by a max pooling layer with a pool size of 2x2, and a dropout regularization with a rate of 0.25. The output of these layers is then flattened and passed to a fully connected layer with 128 neurons and a tanh activation function. Another dropout layer with a rate of 0.5 is added before the final softmax layer, which outputs class probabilities for the input image. The model is compiled with categorical cross-entropy loss and optimized using the Adam optimizer.

In [ ]:
#add strides & activation using tanh
model3 = Sequential()

# a keras convolutional layer = Conv2D

# first conv layer
model3.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(4, 4),
                 activation='tanh',
                 input_shape=input_shape,
                 strides=(2,1)))
# second conv layer
model3.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(4, 4), 
                 activation='tanh'))
model3.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model3.add(Dropout(0.25))

# flatten and put a fully connected layer
model3.add(Flatten())
model3.add(Dense(128, activation='tanh'))
model3.add(Dropout(0.5))

# softmax layer
model3.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

model3.summary()

# usual cross entropy loss
model3.compile(loss=keras.losses.categorical_crossentropy,
              optimizer='adam',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# fit the model
fit_model3 = model3.fit(x_train, y_train,
          batch_size=batch_size,
          epochs=epochs,
          verbose=1,
          validation_data=(x_test, y_test))

# Save the model
model3.save('Model3.h5')

# evaluate the model on test data
model3.evaluate(x_test, y_test)

Model 4

The first convolutional layer uses a filter size of 4x4, a stride of (2,1), tanh activation function, and same padding. The second convolutional layer uses a filter size of 4x4 and the tanh activation function, followed by a max pooling layer with a pool size of 2x2, and a dropout regularization with a rate of 0.25. The output of these layers is then flattened and passed to a fully connected layer with 128 neurons and a tanh activation function. Another dropout layer with a rate of 0.5 is added before the final softmax layer, which outputs class probabilities for the input image. The model is compiled with categorical cross-entropy loss and optimized using the Adam optimizer.

In [ ]:
#add padding
model4 = Sequential()

# first conv layer
model4.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(4, 4),
                 activation='tanh',
                 input_shape=input_shape,
                strides=(2,1) , padding='same')) # input shape = (img_rows, img_cols, 1)
# second conv layer
model4.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(4, 4), 
                 activation='tanh'))
model4.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model4.add(Dropout(0.25))

# flatten and put a fully connected layer
model4.add(Flatten())
model4.add(Dense(128, activation='tanh')) 
model4.add(Dropout(0.5))

# softmax layer
model4.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

model4.summary()

# usual cross entropy loss
model4.compile(loss=keras.losses.categorical_crossentropy,
              optimizer='adam',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# fit the model
fit_model4 = model4.fit(x_train, y_train,
          batch_size=batch_size,
          epochs=epochs,
          verbose=1,
          validation_data=(x_test, y_test))

# evaluate the model on test data
model4.evaluate(x_test, y_test)

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

In [ ]:
def get_optimizer(optimizer_name, learning_rate):
    #'sgd','rmsprop','adam','adagrad'
    optimizer=None
    tf.keras.utils.set_random_seed(42)
    if optimizer_name == 'adagrad': 
        optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.legacy.Adagrad(learning_rate=learning_rate)

    elif 'rmsprop':
        optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.legacy.RMSprop(learning_rate=learning_rate)

    elif'adam' :
        optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.legacy.Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate)
        
    elif 'SGD':
        optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.legacy.SGD(learning_rate=learning_rate)
            
    return optimizer

Use Model 4 in hyperparameter tuning because it has the highest accuracy and lowest value in loss.¶

In [ ]:
def cnn_model(op, epochs, batch_size):
    # set random seed for reproducibility
    tf.random.set_seed(42)
    
    # define the model architecture
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(4, 4), activation='tanh', 
                               input_shape=input_shape, strides=(2, 1), padding='same'),
        tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(4, 4), activation='tanh'),
        tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.25),
        tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='tanh'),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
    ])

    # compile the model with the specified optimizer, loss function, and metrics
    model.compile(
        loss=tf.keras.losses.categorical_crossentropy, 
        optimizer=op,
        metrics=['accuracy']
    )
    
    # fit the model on the training data
    model.fit(
        x_train, y_train, 
        validation_data=(x_test, y_test), 
        epochs=epochs, 
        batch_size=batch_size, 
        verbose=1
    )

    # evaluate the model on the test data
    test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(x_test, y_test)
    
    # print the test accuracy
    print("Test accuracy:", test_acc)

    # return the trained model
    return model

Using adam, adagrad, rmsprop and SGD optimizer, 0.001 and 0.0005 learning rate and batch size in 64 and 128 to do the hyperparameter tuning.¶

In [ ]:
optimizers = ['adam','adagrad','rmsprop','SGD']
learning_rate = [0.001, 0.0005]
batch_size = [64,128]

Model_pool = []
lr_flatten = []
batch_size_flatten = []
optimizers_flatten = []

for lr in learning_rate:
  for op in optimizers:
    opt = get_optimizer(op, lr)
    for bs in batch_size:
      model = cnn_model(opt, 20, bs)
      Model_pool.append(model)
      lr_flatten.append(lr)
      batch_size_flatten.append(bs)
      optimizers_flatten.append(op)

In [ ]:
#Function to store the history of model information for graph plotting
def create_plot(op, epoch, bs):
    tf.keras.utils.set_random_seed(42)
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(4, 4), activation='tanh', 
                               input_shape=input_shape, strides=(2, 1), padding='same'),
        tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(4, 4), activation='tanh'),
        tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.25),
        tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='tanh'),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
    ])
    model.compile(
        loss=tf.keras.losses.categorical_crossentropy, 
        optimizer=op,
        metrics=['accuracy']
    )

    history = model.fit(
        x_train, y_train, 
        validation_data=(x_test, y_test), 
        epochs=epoch, 
        batch_size=bs, 
        verbose=1
    )


    return history
In [ ]:
loss_history = []
  
for lr in learning_rate:
  for op in optimizers:
    opt = get_optimizer(op, lr)
    for loss in ("loss", "val_loss"):
      plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
      for bs in batch_size:
        history = create_plot(opt, 20, bs)
        loss_history.append(history)
        plt.plot(history.history[loss], label = f'Opt {op}, bs {bs}, lr{lr}')
      plt.xlabel("Epochs")
      plt.ylabel(loss)
      plt.title(f'{loss} against epochs')
      plt.legend(loc="upper left")
      plt.show()

### plot the optimizers
for lr in learning_rate:
  for bs in batch_size:
    for loss in ("loss", "val_loss"):
      plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))

      for op in optimizers:
        opt = get_optimizer(op, lr)
        history = create_plot(opt, 20, bs)
        loss_history.append(history)
        plt.plot(history.history[loss], label = f'Opt {op}, bs {bs}, lr{lr}')
      plt.xlabel("Epochs")
      plt.ylabel(loss)
      plt.title(f'{loss} against epochs')
      plt.legend(loc="upper left")
      plt.show()

### plot the learning rate

for op in optimizers:
  for bs in batch_size:
    for loss in ("loss", "val_loss"):
      plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))

      for lr in learning_rate:
        opt = get_optimizer(op, lr)
        history = create_plot(opt, 20, bs)
        loss_history.append(history)
        plt.plot(history.history[loss], label = f'Opt {op}, bs {bs}, lr{lr}')
      plt.xlabel("Epochs")
      plt.ylabel(loss)
      plt.title(f'{loss} against epochs')
      plt.legend(loc="upper left")
      plt.show()

Conclusion¶

We trained several model in this project and try to see the difference of model performance after fine tuning the model. There is a baseline CNN model and the accuracy is 0.9804999828338623. Then we try to add one more convoluted layer to the model and the model accuracy decreased to 0.9786999821662903. So we tried different activation function and apply strides to the model and it's accuracy is 0.9840999841690063 which is improved. We also tried to add padding to the model and the accuracy is 0.9847000241279602. So we decided to use Model 4 to do the hyperparameter tuning. We used adam, adagrad, rmsprop and SGD optimizer, 0.001 and 0.0005 learning rate and batch size in 64 and 128 to do the hyperparameter tuning.
